      <section>                                                         <!--[1-N]-->
       <title>The Bear and the Bull</title>
       <subtitle>Two Different Markets</subtitle>
       <chapter>                                                   <!--[0-N]-->
         <paragraph>
           The Bear Market phase usually lasts five years,
           a measure that results from an "empirical" estimate,
           and therefore should not be considered a certainty.
         </paragraph>                        <!--[0-N]-->
         <paragraph>
           <list type="unordered">                                     <!--[0-N]-->
             <item>Tightening of FED’s monetary policies</item>                                    <!--[1-N]-->
             <item>Strengthening of dollar against all currencies</item>                                                 <!--[1-N]-->
             <item>Weak global economic growth</item>
             <item>Increasing levels of stock index S P 500</item>                                    <!--[1-N]-->
             <item>Great masses of money in ETFs</item>
           </list>
         </paragraph>
         <paragraph>
           The Bullish market consists of three phases: the first is the accumulation; the second is a stage of stability, in the third someone begins to take profit from the rise.
         </paragraph>
         <paragraph>
           <list type="unordered">                                     <!--[0-N]-->
           <item>Increase in demand for gold ETFs</item>                                    <!--[1-N]-->
           <item>Overvalutazion of the dollar</item>
           <item>Worsening of global debt crisis</item>                                    <!--[1-N]-->
           <item>Purchases of gold by central banks</item>
           <item>Change in the cycle of commodities</item>
         </list>
       </paragraph>
       </chapter>
